Yeah, sure, thank you.

00:13:07.599 --> 00:13:11.159
Yeah, that's very interesting about like what you mentioned about personalization.

00:13:11.640 --> 00:13:14.880
I'm curious, like what's the what the roles are?

00:13:14.880 --> 00:13:20.760
So you have like data scientists versus analysts versus machine learning engineers.

00:13:21.039 --> 00:13:26.640
So like what's the balance between those roles and who's building, who is deploying

00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:28.559
this? Yeah, that's a great question.

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:33.200
So we have a separate machine learning, machine learning department.

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:35.359
So we call them DSML or machine learning engineers.

00:13:35.559 --> 00:13:39.960
So we have separate set of machine learning engineers and they focus on building the

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:44.479
software at scale. So these are these are applications that are going to be touching

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:47.919
literally millions and millions of lives in any given day.

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:50.599
So we want to build it at scale and for it to work at scale.

00:13:50.599 --> 00:13:54.119
So we have some amazing human beings who know what they're building at scale.

00:13:54.119 --> 00:13:56.679
So the machine learning engineers and people who can do the MLO.

00:13:56.719 --> 00:13:57.719
So that's one side of it.

00:13:58.359 --> 00:14:02.880
Before we get into that stage, we have the data scientists, the analytics side of data

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:05.919
scientists who get involved, trying to understand what are the right features to think

00:14:05.919 --> 00:14:09.679
about, what are the right things we should optimize for and what kind of business metrics

00:14:09.679 --> 00:14:13.880
can it move? Because we eventually want to be able to plug it back, like I said, into

00:14:13.880 --> 00:14:17.280
the whole conversation of, yes, we can build this amazing algorithm, but what will it

00:14:17.280 --> 00:14:22.080
move for the business? And so we start from there and then we think of it as us running

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:25.719
the first leg of the relay, building it, seeing what works and then handing it off to

00:14:25.719 --> 00:14:28.919
the machine learning engineers who can then build it at scale and then optimize it and

00:14:28.919 --> 00:14:31.200
make it better. So that's how we like to think about it.

00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:32.760
It's a partnership for how we do it.

00:14:36.400 --> 00:14:38.719
Hey, Alan, I see you had a question in the chat, too.

00:14:38.719 --> 00:14:39.520
Want to jump in here?

00:14:41.080 --> 00:14:45.840
Yeah, thanks. I'm really curious, you mentioned when you're sort of introducing

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:50.719
yourself that you've been in places where I think maybe I read this in places where

00:14:50.719 --> 00:14:53.119
analytics was not at the table, like as a partner.

00:14:53.359 --> 00:14:56.479
I'm curious if coming to DoorDash, was it already there?

00:14:56.479 --> 00:15:01.799
Was that already established or did you have to work to make that partnership really

00:15:01.799 --> 00:15:04.400
effective? I'm just curious what that kind of journey was like.

00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:08.200
How do you become really visible as a partner?

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:13.880
So the honest answer is when I came to DoorDash, it was already established.

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:18.239
The people who had established it had made sure that that was part of the secret for

00:15:18.239 --> 00:15:21.960
why DoorDash grew as it grew and how we would find out what it could do.

00:15:22.280 --> 00:15:26.400
What we are trying to do, though, is now that DoorDash has acquired Volt and I've now

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:28.719
moved from DoorDash to Volt, we're trying to bring the same culture here.

00:15:28.719 --> 00:15:32.840
So for me, it's an ability of seeing what the future can look like and trying to bring

00:15:32.840 --> 00:15:36.400
the future again to companies that we don't have it in its truest sense.

00:15:37.039 --> 00:15:40.280
And to your point, what I've seen in the past, I've worked in other companies where

00:15:40.919 --> 00:15:44.239
you could have a role, you could have the title, but you're often consulted after the

00:15:44.239 --> 00:15:46.400
fact, where you can't effectively change things.

00:15:46.400 --> 00:15:47.599
You can only measure things.

00:15:47.919 --> 00:15:49.320
So you're mostly the measurer.

00:15:49.359 --> 00:15:51.960
I was mostly the measurer rather than the influencer.

00:15:51.960 --> 00:15:54.000
So you can measure things and anybody can measure it.

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:58.919
But having a say and saying, yep, don't do this or do this or do this because this

00:15:58.919 --> 00:16:02.320
makes sense. I think that gives you a totally different responsibility and skin in the

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:03.719
game. And that makes it all the more fun.

00:16:04.440 --> 00:16:08.239
That's what I've seen. But yeah, so to answer your question, already at DoorDash, not at

00:16:08.239 --> 00:16:10.520
Volt. And so at Volt, I'm trying to build that culture.

00:16:11.640 --> 00:16:15.320
That's great. That environment where you can experiment and have business buying for

00:16:15.320 --> 00:16:20.320
doing that and then bringing things into action sounds really cool.

00:16:20.559 --> 00:16:21.559
Sounds like a neat environment.

00:16:22.960 --> 00:16:23.960
Thanks.

00:16:25.080 --> 00:16:28.919
I know you mentioned some of the experimentation that you're doing, but I remember

00:16:28.919 --> 00:16:33.280
from our our pre-call, you mentioned like there's millions or maybe it was billions of

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:35.320
experiments happening at one time.

00:16:35.320 --> 00:16:39.599
Could you just share a little bit more about that and like that, that huge number

00:16:39.599 --> 00:16:40.599
that's happening?

00:16:41.159 --> 00:16:45.640
Yeah, so at any given point in time, my understanding is we have three to five

00:16:45.640 --> 00:16:48.320
thousand different experiments going on at any point in time.

00:16:48.359 --> 00:16:51.640
And so if you're accumulating some data for multiple weeks, multiple months, you're

00:16:51.640 --> 00:16:53.479
only talking about tens of thousands of experiments.

00:16:53.799 --> 00:16:58.000
And so the reason is not to experiment ourselves and increment ourselves into

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.440
irrelevance. It's about trying to understand truly what works and what doesn't.

00:17:01.880 --> 00:17:05.079
And there is a culture, like I said, it's not just us doing it.

00:17:06.239 --> 00:17:08.239
As the saying goes, you can't clap with one hand.

00:17:09.160 --> 00:17:12.439
The other side of the party also needs to come to the dance and also dance.

00:17:12.599 --> 00:17:15.719
So the business comes down and says, we think there's an amazing idea, but we want

00:17:15.719 --> 00:17:18.239
to be really sure this is the right thing to put our money on.

00:17:18.479 --> 00:17:20.319
Can we experiment with this? We experimented.

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:23.239
We see what the increment is. We say we get X percent more.

00:17:23.560 --> 00:17:25.719
Let's put let's go all in or it doesn't work.

00:17:25.719 --> 00:17:28.599
Let's try something else. And so I think that's a fun part to be in.

00:17:28.680 --> 00:17:30.920
And so the team sees value and the businesses value.

00:17:32.079 --> 00:17:35.400
So that's that's what it is. So what we do have is, like I said, the machine

00:17:35.400 --> 00:17:36.760
learning models are at scale.

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:41.680
The last that I remember from a publicly released document was we have around a

00:17:41.680 --> 00:17:46.160
billion different predictions made at any given point on a given day because we

00:17:46.160 --> 00:17:50.520
have all the personalization systems, all the dashes who deliver food, all the

00:17:50.520 --> 00:17:53.560
merchants who show up on the everything is personalized at scale.

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:55.199
We have a machine learning platform that are set.

00:17:55.199 --> 00:17:56.959
So that's the kind of scale that we are talking about.

00:17:59.760 --> 00:18:00.760
Very impressive.

00:18:01.199 --> 00:18:04.680
I am I see quite a few questions coming into the chat here.

00:18:04.680 --> 00:18:07.680
Let's see. Joseph, you have one on spatial analysis.

00:18:07.680 --> 00:18:12.719
Do you want to jump in? Yeah, I was just curious about like how, you know, you

00:18:12.719 --> 00:18:17.599
apply things like isochrones or nearest neighbor analysis to find like, all right,

00:18:17.599 --> 00:18:21.000
we have an order in this neighborhood, the restaurants here, like where is your

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:24.119
nearest dasher and like kind of what that looks like at enterprise scale?

00:18:25.520 --> 00:18:30.560
Yeah, so, yeah, we probably could talk to that, but the answer to the question is

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:34.160
I probably can't point to just one particular special analysis we do or one

00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:34.959
particular thing we do.

00:18:35.800 --> 00:18:39.199
Isochrone is definitely one thing we do to try to understand how do we timebox it

00:18:39.199 --> 00:18:43.599
and because we pay for time and not for like the dashers are paid based on how

00:18:43.719 --> 00:18:46.079
much they spend with us and the time is money.

00:18:46.079 --> 00:18:48.280
So we do a lot of time related special analysis.

00:18:49.439 --> 00:18:52.760
We don't analyze per se because we have a system.

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:56.319
The system takes care of all the routing and optimization.

00:18:56.319 --> 00:18:57.359
Yes, we contribute to it.

00:18:57.359 --> 00:18:59.439
We try to figure out what how can we make better.

00:19:00.319 --> 00:19:03.640
But we don't spend a lot of time analyzing things like who's the nearest

00:19:03.640 --> 00:19:04.839
available driver.

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:10.160
We more worry about how do we make the supply of a particular market more

00:19:10.160 --> 00:19:14.319
balanced, knowing what we know and how do we mobilize them better and how do we

00:19:14.319 --> 00:19:15.239
mobilize them faster?

00:19:15.479 --> 00:19:18.839
If we mobilize them better and if you have enough number of people ready to

00:19:18.839 --> 00:19:22.280
deliver, the system is smart enough to figure out who to pick for the next order.

00:19:22.280 --> 00:19:24.079
So that's not something we need to solve for.

00:19:24.079 --> 00:19:25.479
We need to solve for the second and third order.

00:19:27.479 --> 00:19:27.839
Thank you.

00:19:30.439 --> 00:19:35.920
Bill, I think you sometimes like me to ask the question, so if you want to ask

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:41.359
it, jump in, but I see you wrote one would assume that DoorDash, Uber Eats and

00:19:41.359 --> 00:19:46.560
others in the space would need to consume the same type of data from places like

00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:49.680
McDonald's or Kroger's and local restaurants.

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:54.880
Is there a standard for the way data is structured in this industry, the data

00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:57.319
like item descriptions, price or location?

00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:04.800
So, unfortunately or fortunately, dusting has never been standardized.

00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:09.479
So as anybody who's worked in retail, any kind of retail knows that because all of

00:20:09.479 --> 00:20:13.439
this is manually created, if you imagine how a restaurant sets up a menu, it's a

00:20:13.439 --> 00:20:16.359
human being at a restaurant setting up a menu for their own restaurant.

00:20:16.359 --> 00:20:19.280
So there is no standard way that you can get it sorted out.

00:20:19.560 --> 00:20:22.439
Even the biggest chains don't agree on how the data is going to look like.

00:20:22.439 --> 00:20:26.280
So we do a lot of work in-house to come up with our own taxonomies.

00:20:26.280 --> 00:20:28.760
There's a lot of effort involved in how do we taxonomize this?

00:20:29.040 --> 00:20:30.880
How do we understand what is actually a starter?

00:20:30.880 --> 00:20:33.800
Is the side dish versus the main dish?

00:20:33.800 --> 00:20:35.160
What is the actual price point?

00:20:35.599 --> 00:20:37.719
We do a lot of cleaning up work on the backend.

00:20:38.439 --> 00:20:42.520
I guess it can be solved by better data entry mechanisms, but none of the

00:20:42.520 --> 00:20:47.520
industries have a standard format in which it's shared and I don't think there

00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:51.000
has been a case for trying to standardize it because like I said at the end of the

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:55.400
day, these are human beings at the end of the day who are running their own small

00:20:55.400 --> 00:20:58.719
mom-and-pop shops trying to set up their own business and it's very hard for them

00:20:58.719 --> 00:21:02.439
to add another friction point to tell them how to enter data in a particular way.

00:21:02.760 --> 00:21:06.119
So all they're trying to do is copy their menu from the real world into the digital

00:21:06.119 --> 00:21:08.079
world and there's only so much they can do with that.

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:15.280
This is a new term I hadn't heard of, Mark, zombie retention.

00:21:15.280 --> 00:21:17.319
Do you want to jump in and ask that?

00:21:20.719 --> 00:21:21.680
Yeah, sure.

00:21:21.680 --> 00:21:27.239
I was, so I put a question in the chat about like, how do you, when you're, you

00:21:27.239 --> 00:21:31.839
mentioned earlier modeling or like running experiments on retention and I

00:21:31.839 --> 00:21:34.959
have kind of a twofold question, if that's all right, one was about like

00:21:34.959 --> 00:21:39.839
zombie retention, which is the case of somebody churns and like in a subscription

00:21:39.839 --> 00:21:44.680
model, you know, somebody churns, they don't necessarily come back, but when

00:21:44.680 --> 00:21:48.599
it's sort of like voluntary leaving and coming back like DoorDash, I imagine

00:21:48.599 --> 00:21:53.599
there's a case where somebody churns for like a long time and then makes a return.

00:21:54.560 --> 00:21:59.079
Like, I don't know, a year or six months or whatever later is the first part is

00:21:59.079 --> 00:22:06.640
like, how do you handle that if, if you do, and then the, the, the second was

00:22:06.640 --> 00:22:13.560
like, it's kind of relatedly, how do you handle like a problem of anonymous

00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:18.199
versus like logged in customers and keeping track of who's who, from like

00:22:18.199 --> 00:22:20.839
an experiment, like in an attribution level.

00:22:22.079 --> 00:22:22.280
Sure.

00:22:22.880 --> 00:22:27.479
Talking about the people who get reactivated, we call them reactivated

00:22:27.479 --> 00:22:32.400
people, the fact that the way we look at reactive people is we understand that

00:22:32.400 --> 00:22:35.400
not everyone has the need to use the platform the same way that every other

00:22:35.400 --> 00:22:35.680
person.

00:22:35.800 --> 00:22:39.040
So some people are going to come back once in a while, go away, then open up

00:22:39.040 --> 00:22:40.239
the app again, come back again.

00:22:40.239 --> 00:22:44.959
So we do understand there is a need and potential for people to come that way.

00:22:44.959 --> 00:22:48.000
So we don't treat them any differently to how we treat others.

00:22:48.239 --> 00:22:50.800
What we do want to understand is why does it happen more?

00:22:50.920 --> 00:22:52.920
So we have a threshold for how much it can happen.

00:22:52.959 --> 00:22:56.160
If it happens beyond that level, then you want to understand why, or if it goes

00:22:56.160 --> 00:22:58.839
beyond that level, you want to understand why, but we understand that it is an

00:22:58.839 --> 00:23:00.920
acceptable threshold of people who will do that.

00:23:00.920 --> 00:23:02.119
And that's the marketing behavior.

00:23:02.239 --> 00:23:05.800
People are going to open up once a year or once in six months or so that

00:23:05.800 --> 00:23:06.560
they're going to do that.

00:23:06.560 --> 00:23:10.479
But if it gets anywhere outside that threshold is when we start looking into

00:23:10.479 --> 00:23:10.640
it.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:15.560
And so we look into why, what happens, what market did we do something that

00:23:15.560 --> 00:23:16.520
somebody else do something.

00:23:16.520 --> 00:23:17.640
So that's what we look at.

00:23:18.560 --> 00:23:20.719
In terms of the other question on logged in, this is logged out.

00:23:21.040 --> 00:23:25.560
Most of our experimentation is on logged in, you can't shop on a pad, like you

00:23:25.560 --> 00:23:26.719
can't buy without logging in.

00:23:26.719 --> 00:23:30.640
So more often than not, anything related to conversion related stuff is logged in.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:34.839
But if you're just about the app usage and things on the app feature, the logged

00:23:34.839 --> 00:23:38.400
out people mostly, unless they have some kind of other identifier that they can

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:42.079
tie them to, they probably won't be considered in the export, because the

00:23:42.079 --> 00:23:43.560
experiment won't load for those people.

00:23:43.560 --> 00:23:46.280
If they're not logged in, it gets featured based on who they are.

00:23:46.800 --> 00:23:51.319
It's each, each person is in a bucket, so they get a lot of things that they need

00:23:51.319 --> 00:23:53.199
to see based on the logged in status.

00:23:54.160 --> 00:23:55.079
Okay, cool.

00:23:55.119 --> 00:23:55.479
Thank you.

00:23:59.079 --> 00:24:01.359
I think Arsenis, you had another question in the chat.

00:24:01.359 --> 00:24:02.079
Want to jump in?

00:24:04.439 --> 00:24:04.880
Sure.

00:24:04.959 --> 00:24:10.680
So yeah, this was just about your experience going from DoorDash to Walt.

00:24:11.280 --> 00:24:15.839
I'm kind of curious about the data science workflows in between them, whether

00:24:15.839 --> 00:24:19.599
you noticed any differences and you could, and if you could maybe talk about

00:24:19.599 --> 00:24:25.359
that a little, So in terms of the workflow, I think given we are similar

00:24:25.359 --> 00:24:29.160
industry, same, almost same company, similar industries, the approaches to

00:24:29.160 --> 00:24:30.160
solving the problem are the same.

00:24:30.160 --> 00:24:33.479
It's just that where the problem, where we got involved and how we started

00:24:33.479 --> 00:24:34.439
solving the problem was different.

00:24:34.439 --> 00:24:38.359
So like I said, the workflow at DoorDash is more around, we think about the

00:24:38.359 --> 00:24:40.000
problem, everyone comes together.

00:24:40.079 --> 00:24:44.560
I should say, if it's the right thing to solve, and then we go away trying to

00:24:44.560 --> 00:24:46.239
understand how do we solve it?

00:24:46.239 --> 00:24:47.000
How do you build for it?

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:47.520
What do we do?

00:24:47.640 --> 00:24:50.119
So there's a different workflow, which is, there's a deep dive first.

00:24:50.479 --> 00:24:53.719
Then it goes into running a lot of smaller experiments.

00:24:54.040 --> 00:24:56.000
Then after the experiments are done is when we actually start building the

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:58.119
feature, then we'll roll the feature out, et cetera, et cetera.

00:24:58.640 --> 00:25:01.079
At Walt, it's slightly different where we first build a feature.

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:02.920
Then we say, okay, this is the right feature to build.

00:25:03.119 --> 00:25:05.839
Then we come back and see, did it work or not?

00:25:05.839 --> 00:25:07.839
And then we do a deep dive, why did it not work?

00:25:07.839 --> 00:25:08.800
What would you have done differently?

00:25:08.800 --> 00:25:12.160
So I think then it becomes something of, and there's the sunk cost

00:25:12.160 --> 00:25:14.479
fallacy with doing things like that, because once you spend time doing

00:25:14.479 --> 00:25:17.680
something, you probably want to always try to find out if there is some way we

00:25:17.680 --> 00:25:20.719
can make this work rather than saying if it's the right thing we should build.

00:25:20.719 --> 00:25:23.920
So that's, there's a difference in the workflows here, but other than that,

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:25.640
we use similar systems, similar tooling.

00:25:26.079 --> 00:25:27.560
So not a lot is different.

00:25:27.599 --> 00:25:30.239
I would say in terms of how we get the data from where it needs

00:25:30.239 --> 00:25:31.359
to be to what it needs to be.

00:25:35.800 --> 00:25:36.800
I hope that answers your question.

00:25:39.599 --> 00:25:39.880
Yep.

00:25:40.880 --> 00:25:42.359
Would it be okay to ask a follow-up here?

00:25:42.520 --> 00:25:43.319
Yeah, of course.

00:25:43.959 --> 00:25:44.199
Yeah.

00:25:44.199 --> 00:25:50.439
So, so that's an interesting thing because, so in one instance, Dordodash

00:25:50.439 --> 00:25:53.520
you were talking about, it's more, you kind of start from the question

00:25:53.959 --> 00:25:55.319
and then build to the tool.

00:25:55.640 --> 00:25:58.920
Whereas it sounds like with Walt, it's going kind of the other

00:25:58.920 --> 00:26:00.000
way in the other direction.

00:26:00.319 --> 00:26:02.560
Like we're going to build these tools and all that, and then we're going to

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:05.920
see how well they work to solve whatever question you have.

00:26:06.439 --> 00:26:13.640
So my, my question around that is how, how do how do the teams differ in

00:26:13.680 --> 00:26:18.800
their approaches to building models and kind of answering questions?

00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:23.359
And which one would you say, well, you know, it's, I'm not going to ask

00:26:23.359 --> 00:26:26.520
like which one works better, but what would you say are the advantages

00:26:26.520 --> 00:26:29.479
and disadvantages of either from, from that perspective?

00:26:30.680 --> 00:26:32.880
So I probably won't try to compare it too much.

00:26:32.880 --> 00:26:37.359
What I would say is the benefit of the Dordodash approach is not having to

00:26:37.359 --> 00:26:42.719
waste time and effort on things that don't work, but the loss of that effort

00:26:42.719 --> 00:26:46.040
is a lot of ideas that actually might not look good on paper might end up

00:26:46.040 --> 00:26:48.560
doing pretty good because we can never say that we know everything.

00:26:48.599 --> 00:26:51.719
So if you knew everything and we knew, figured out how things would

00:26:51.719 --> 00:26:53.439
work, we would not come up with amazing ideas.

00:26:53.439 --> 00:26:55.920
So I think there is pros and cons of both techniques.

00:26:55.920 --> 00:26:57.959
So trying to find that balance is what you're trying to do.

00:26:58.359 --> 00:27:01.680
Like Walt builds a lot of amazing, what we call bold, great products.

00:27:02.280 --> 00:27:05.680
We are really proud of what we build and really in that customer experience.

00:27:06.079 --> 00:27:09.000
So some of these things are not quantifiable in a way, so

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:10.199
it would be hard to justify.

00:27:10.199 --> 00:27:11.719
So that would be the pro and con.

00:27:11.719 --> 00:27:13.599
The pros is not wasting time on things.

00:27:13.599 --> 00:27:16.599
The con would be not getting time to do actual things that

00:27:17.439 --> 00:27:18.599
it all doesn't look good on paper.

00:27:18.599 --> 00:27:21.800
So that's, those are the challenges that we're trying to face and seeing

00:27:21.800 --> 00:27:23.040
how we balance a bit of both.

00:27:23.319 --> 00:27:27.839
So something I wanted to ask is, I know sometimes featured

00:27:27.839 --> 00:27:30.000
leaders might be from huge companies.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:33.439
So if people are from a smaller team, they might not right away

00:27:33.439 --> 00:27:35.680
see how some of it might relate.

00:27:36.119 --> 00:27:39.839
But I was wondering if you have any advice for somebody who's maybe on it,

00:27:40.359 --> 00:27:44.760
maybe the first data scientist or on a small team of data scientists for

00:27:44.760 --> 00:27:46.719
making an impact on the business.

00:27:47.760 --> 00:27:49.439
So this is something I often get asked.

00:27:49.640 --> 00:27:53.760
I tell them if the work that we do as a team analytics team or data team or

00:27:53.760 --> 00:27:55.719
data science team, that's not direct.

00:27:55.760 --> 00:27:58.400
We don't know how it directly changes how the business works.

