00:40:57.000 --> 00:40:59.719
And then his comment would be, if you didn't expect, that's the

00:40:59.719 --> 00:41:00.840
whole point of experiments.

00:41:00.919 --> 00:41:02.399
It's to fail and to learn things.

00:41:02.399 --> 00:41:03.760
If you didn't fail, you would never learn.

00:41:03.760 --> 00:41:06.959
So it's that culture is built in, in the business.

00:41:06.959 --> 00:41:09.959
And so what happens is the business comes to us and says, we want to build this

00:41:09.959 --> 00:41:13.000
new, go to a new market or build this new product or build this new feature

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:17.120
or whatever it is, um, let's do it in an incremental fashion and let's measure

00:41:17.120 --> 00:41:20.360
along the way and make sure if it's the right thing to do, uh, if it's useless,

00:41:20.360 --> 00:41:21.479
let's throw it out the window.

00:41:21.479 --> 00:41:22.959
If it's great, let's evolve it.

00:41:22.959 --> 00:41:24.239
And so that definitely happens.

00:41:24.239 --> 00:41:27.320
So that's what that, that different, that, that, that happens, right?

00:41:27.320 --> 00:41:30.239
Like I said, it can't, you can't clap with one hand.

00:41:30.239 --> 00:41:34.239
So it's not just us championing how we do things or evolving out to things.

00:41:34.239 --> 00:41:37.320
It's the business also wanting to do things in a better way.

00:41:37.320 --> 00:41:39.040
And so that's, that's where this comes from.

00:41:41.840 --> 00:41:42.360
Thank you.

00:41:43.320 --> 00:41:45.879
I know Bill had a question a little bit earlier.

00:41:45.879 --> 00:41:47.639
Bill, do you want to jump in?

00:41:51.159 --> 00:41:51.639
I can read.

00:41:51.879 --> 00:41:52.360
Okay.

00:41:52.560 --> 00:41:55.159
The question was, um, what role do Microsoft products?

00:41:55.159 --> 00:42:00.439
So Excel copilot power BI play in your data presentation and the review of

00:42:00.439 --> 00:42:03.080
your results by internal customers?

00:42:04.800 --> 00:42:05.000
Yeah.

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:11.360
Um, so we do use, um, I don't think we have a lot of Microsoft products as such.

00:42:11.399 --> 00:42:14.040
Um, yes, obviously we do use a lot.

00:42:14.520 --> 00:42:17.639
There's nobody who does not use Excel, but we don't use a lot of the other things.

00:42:17.639 --> 00:42:20.959
So all our presentations are on Google slides.

00:42:21.159 --> 00:42:22.719
We do a lot of the document culture.

00:42:22.719 --> 00:42:23.760
So everything is written down.

00:42:23.760 --> 00:42:26.639
So anything that you need to make a decision on, be it an experimental

00:42:26.639 --> 00:42:29.719
feature or be it a business decision, everything is written down and somebody

00:42:29.719 --> 00:42:32.760
comments on the talk and says if it's the right thing to do and if it's the right.

00:42:32.919 --> 00:42:36.639
So it's all a lot of Google docs is what we work on.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:42.679
Um, and we use, uh, Looker from Google, which is the visualization platform

00:42:42.679 --> 00:42:44.159
to share dashboards and stuff like that.

00:42:44.520 --> 00:42:46.040
But dashboards are best dashboards.

00:42:46.080 --> 00:42:48.639
You know, the decisions are made on a document, uh, be it

00:42:48.679 --> 00:42:49.879
investing money in a place.

00:42:49.959 --> 00:42:52.399
We're shutting down a feature or being that pickup feature.

00:42:52.800 --> 00:42:56.199
Everyone writes up an experimental doc, um, talk about what the feedback

00:42:56.199 --> 00:42:57.560
has been or what the output has been.

00:42:57.879 --> 00:42:59.239
And then people ask questions there.

00:42:59.239 --> 00:43:02.919
And then the decision is made there in the document on what that's what we do.

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:06.600
Thank you.

00:43:09.199 --> 00:43:12.840
Someone's trying to jump in and ask something, but right.

00:43:12.840 --> 00:43:15.760
Feel free to raise your hand after and jump in.

00:43:16.399 --> 00:43:20.879
But, um, I see Sal, you had a question when I asked that next.

00:43:25.320 --> 00:43:25.760
Okay.

00:43:25.800 --> 00:43:28.760
I think there's a little bit of background noise for you.

00:43:28.760 --> 00:43:30.560
So if you don't mind, I'll ask it.

00:43:31.520 --> 00:43:31.840
Okay.

00:43:33.399 --> 00:43:37.040
Um, so the question was, how do you and your team deal with ambiguous data

00:43:37.040 --> 00:43:39.479
signals where things are not certain?

00:43:40.879 --> 00:43:41.120
Yeah.

00:43:41.280 --> 00:43:44.560
Um, I'd like to understand more by more on what those ambiguous

00:43:44.560 --> 00:43:46.040
data signals could be solved.

00:43:46.479 --> 00:43:48.639
Um, because it could mean anything.

00:43:51.479 --> 00:43:51.840
Yeah.

00:43:51.840 --> 00:43:53.439
So like, I think there's two things.

00:43:53.439 --> 00:43:55.959
There's external ambiguity and internal.

00:43:56.040 --> 00:44:01.399
So external would be like, uh, you know, let's say credit scores

00:44:01.399 --> 00:44:03.639
are going down, but income is going up, right?

00:44:03.639 --> 00:44:06.560
Like, so I assume we're doing the internal, right.

00:44:07.120 --> 00:44:11.159
We've had a lot of situations where one data set has 80% coverage,

00:44:11.719 --> 00:44:12.120
right.

00:44:17.120 --> 00:44:17.479
Fair enough.

00:44:17.479 --> 00:44:17.959
That makes sense.

00:44:18.800 --> 00:44:19.239
No worries.

00:44:19.399 --> 00:44:22.399
So internal, I can talk about the internal data points.

00:44:22.439 --> 00:44:25.120
We will absolutely make sure that we understand.

00:44:25.159 --> 00:44:27.520
So data quality and lineage is a massive thing for us.

00:44:27.560 --> 00:44:31.239
We spend a lot of time and effort on understanding how we track something,

00:44:31.239 --> 00:44:33.280
where it is tracked from, what is the coverage for it?

00:44:33.760 --> 00:44:35.360
Uh, we have monitors for it.

00:44:35.399 --> 00:44:38.520
So we know at any point in time, what is the quality of our data?

00:44:38.760 --> 00:44:41.520
Um, and because like I said, we're extremely obsessed with metrics.

00:44:41.959 --> 00:44:44.879
Uh, even if something moves by a couple of basis points, you know,

00:44:44.879 --> 00:44:47.879
immediately, if it's a moment due to us, due to the market or due

00:44:47.879 --> 00:44:48.719
to the data being wrong.

00:44:48.719 --> 00:44:51.239
And so if, if anything looks good to be true, the first

00:44:51.239 --> 00:44:52.280
question is data is wrong.

00:44:52.320 --> 00:44:55.639
So because that has been told so many times, that doesn't

00:44:55.639 --> 00:44:57.560
happen anytime anymore.

00:44:57.560 --> 00:44:59.040
It hasn't happened in a long, long time.

00:44:59.360 --> 00:45:01.719
So we have tight control over the data quality of everything

00:45:01.719 --> 00:45:02.840
that we fight through internet.

00:45:03.439 --> 00:45:05.919
On external data, we think that we don't have control over example,

00:45:06.040 --> 00:45:09.199
market share data that we get, or app download data from download

00:45:09.199 --> 00:45:10.199
partners and stuff like that.

00:45:10.600 --> 00:45:14.120
The only way we provide credibility to it is by trying to triangulate

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:17.800
it with something else, which is one other external data and also

00:45:17.800 --> 00:45:21.040
our in-house internal data, try to find a proxy for it and then

00:45:21.040 --> 00:45:22.159
seeing if that all makes sense.

00:45:22.159 --> 00:45:25.040
So we never trust anything until we can triangulate it.

00:45:25.040 --> 00:45:26.679
And we know for sure that makes sense.

00:45:26.959 --> 00:45:29.399
So for example, the same external party would also be tracking us and

00:45:29.399 --> 00:45:30.840
providing a version of our data.

00:45:31.120 --> 00:45:34.959
And so we'd buy that too and say, we know what, what is true for us.

00:45:34.959 --> 00:45:38.360
We know what they are saying, and then apply that pinch of salt on the

00:45:38.360 --> 00:45:39.679
other external data and try to take it.

00:45:39.679 --> 00:45:42.280
So there's always going to be an element of uncertainty with that.

00:45:42.280 --> 00:45:45.479
So we don't make big decisions on external data, but we always, it's

00:45:45.479 --> 00:45:46.239
always good to understand.

00:45:46.239 --> 00:45:47.239
So we try to triangulate it.

00:45:47.239 --> 00:45:47.840
So that's what we do.

00:45:52.520 --> 00:45:53.080
Thank you.

00:45:53.879 --> 00:45:57.080
Um, I see George asked a question in the chat and there's a star there.

00:45:57.080 --> 00:46:01.439
So I'll ask it, but it was, how do you account for the influence of

00:46:01.439 --> 00:46:03.360
the models on the outcomes you see?

00:46:03.399 --> 00:46:07.439
For example, did the user purchase or sign up for DoorDash because of

00:46:07.439 --> 00:46:09.120
the recommendation or marketing?

00:46:10.399 --> 00:46:10.679
Yeah.

00:46:11.159 --> 00:46:14.800
So I'm probably not sure exactly.

00:46:14.800 --> 00:46:18.080
I understand if you're trying to ask me, what is the impact of every

00:46:18.080 --> 00:46:20.239
model that we build and do we ladder up to it?

00:46:20.639 --> 00:46:22.800
Uh, some models, yes, we do understand it.

00:46:22.800 --> 00:46:25.879
So if it's a personalization algorithm, it's a recommendation algorithm.

00:46:25.879 --> 00:46:29.719
We know, for example, we showed a restaurant to a person consumer and

00:46:29.719 --> 00:46:30.959
she clicked on it and she bought it.

00:46:31.199 --> 00:46:33.080
We know exactly bang on because we track it.

00:46:33.479 --> 00:46:35.560
Or we showed a delivery order to a delivery person.

00:46:35.560 --> 00:46:38.000
He picked it because it was most profitable for him.

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:38.800
And then he delivered it.

00:46:39.280 --> 00:46:39.679
Bang on.

00:46:39.679 --> 00:46:40.879
We know exactly who that was.

00:46:40.879 --> 00:46:43.399
So there's not a need for a lot of attribution there.

00:46:43.479 --> 00:46:44.639
We know exactly who did what.

00:46:44.639 --> 00:46:47.479
And therefore we try to understand if we do this model out, what

00:46:47.479 --> 00:46:48.840
is the impact to the business?

00:46:49.239 --> 00:46:53.159
In cases like marketing, where we make marketing spend decisions.

00:46:53.520 --> 00:46:55.479
Um, obviously we don't have that level of knowledge.

00:46:55.479 --> 00:46:57.639
So we do use aggregated models.

00:46:57.639 --> 00:47:00.320
So for example, we have market mix models that end up understanding.

00:47:00.760 --> 00:47:01.800
What is the decision?

00:47:02.120 --> 00:47:05.679
What is the overall impact of the business short term, long term from a

00:47:05.679 --> 00:47:08.760
particular marketing vision that we decide to spend more money on Facebook

00:47:08.760 --> 00:47:09.800
versus Google and stuff like that.

00:47:09.800 --> 00:47:11.959
So that's the level of attribution we can do.

00:47:11.959 --> 00:47:15.280
We don't tend to go too deep, not because we can't, but because we find

00:47:15.280 --> 00:47:21.399
that that level of granularity is not as beneficial as, um, given how fast

00:47:21.399 --> 00:47:25.120
we move and how sometimes we have to make irrational decisions in the world

00:47:25.120 --> 00:47:28.000
of marketing and branding, where not everything that you see is

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:28.959
not what you can measure.

00:47:28.959 --> 00:47:30.719
So you just have to take something with a pinch of salt.

00:47:33.919 --> 00:47:37.080
So you're thinking about your own career journey.

00:47:37.199 --> 00:47:41.360
Uh, is there a piece of advice that you've either received from

00:47:41.360 --> 00:47:44.520
somebody or a piece of advice that you've given that you'd

00:47:44.520 --> 00:47:45.760
be open to sharing with us?

00:47:47.439 --> 00:47:52.399
Um, so the one thing that I've, I've heard from, and so this is completely

00:47:52.399 --> 00:47:55.600
probably tangential to what we're talking about is if we don't talk

00:47:55.639 --> 00:47:58.800
about the work we do, nobody knows what it is.

00:47:58.840 --> 00:47:59.879
And so I've taken that.

00:48:00.600 --> 00:48:03.280
So a lot of times we do some amazing, this is something I tell my team,

00:48:03.320 --> 00:48:06.360
you do some amazing work, but you don't want to talk to anyone about it

00:48:06.360 --> 00:48:09.040
because you assume people automatically figure out about your work, come

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:11.560
understand what it is, and then appreciate you for it.

00:48:11.560 --> 00:48:12.639
That doesn't happen.

00:48:12.639 --> 00:48:16.360
And so at scale, especially if you have a great idea, what we do believe

00:48:16.360 --> 00:48:19.919
in is you have to be vocal about your idea and talk about why that makes

00:48:19.919 --> 00:48:22.919
sense, what is the great project you've done, why, how is it impacting the

00:48:22.919 --> 00:48:24.760
business if we don't do it?

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:29.159
Um, and you just worry that nobody appreciates what you do or things

00:48:29.159 --> 00:48:34.639
don't happen for yourself that, um, passive, uh, credibility never happens.

00:48:34.639 --> 00:48:36.320
It needs to, you need to take an active foot in it.

00:48:36.320 --> 00:48:37.800
It's what I've been told.

00:48:37.800 --> 00:48:38.439
I was advised.

00:48:38.439 --> 00:48:40.760
I've taken it to heart and that's what I tell my team.

00:48:40.760 --> 00:48:42.280
So we create forums for the team.

00:48:42.280 --> 00:48:44.679
So the teams can come share their ideas, the things that they've done.

00:48:45.040 --> 00:48:48.280
We push our teams to be vocal about things that they find are wrong.

00:48:48.280 --> 00:48:51.280
If they see something, we ask them to say something and fix it.

00:48:51.560 --> 00:48:56.320
And so there is a lot of effort on, um, being vocal about the work and being

00:48:56.320 --> 00:48:59.679
in the data analytics space where everyone likes to be with their stuff.

00:48:59.719 --> 00:49:00.600
Not be bothered.

00:49:00.639 --> 00:49:01.520
Tell me what you need to do.

00:49:01.520 --> 00:49:02.439
I'll do and walk away.

00:49:02.800 --> 00:49:06.439
We push people to be a bit uncomfortable and actually speak

00:49:06.439 --> 00:49:08.040
out and make themselves heard.

00:49:08.040 --> 00:49:12.040
So I think that's something that I've learned and I pass on to my teams.

00:49:15.399 --> 00:49:18.399
How do you actually go about like doing that too?

00:49:18.439 --> 00:49:19.439
Like what's the.

00:49:19.800 --> 00:49:23.719
So one thing is we do create, we do make sure that the work that the team does

00:49:23.719 --> 00:49:26.239
is incredibly technical and complicated.

00:49:26.239 --> 00:49:29.199
So instead of boring the team with boring everyone about, we did the

00:49:29.199 --> 00:49:31.679
CB test and we saw this, it was like, no.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:35.639
So if you do this, you get X back and trying to translate that, translate

00:49:35.639 --> 00:49:37.040
math into English is what I do.

00:49:37.120 --> 00:49:40.320
And I try to teach the team, but how do you translate your math into English?

00:49:40.719 --> 00:49:43.600
So we teach people on the world that they do.

00:49:43.639 --> 00:49:48.800
So I do that and I try to help my team do that at scale, uh, which helps them.

00:49:49.159 --> 00:49:53.919
Then that transition helps us understand the business problems in the business

00:49:53.919 --> 00:49:57.199
this lens, and rather than understanding it completely from a technical or a

00:49:57.199 --> 00:50:00.679
data lens, which stops us from being limited by what we can do, and then

00:50:00.679 --> 00:50:03.639
opens up the possibility to what all we could potentially do and solve.

